    "created_at": "2015-03-02T19:45:50Z",
    "updated_at": "2015-03-02T19:45:50Z",
    "body": "For features like sound generic drop, the compiler needs to know which pointers are owning and which are borrowing.  We don't want to arbitrarily say that `*mut T` is owning for some `T` and borrowing for others.  That's a global decision for each `T`, but most types of objects can in fact be owned in some contexts and borrowed in others.\n\n> Or I have to do funny things like sending `(T,)`.\n\nThe non-funny version of this is your own newtype struct with a pub field that exposes the raw pointer.  You'd impl `Send` on that struct. Then you're saying that pointers generated _a specific way_ are safe to send, rather than any `*mut` that happens to point to a `T`.\n\n> There seems to be no reason to remove that feature.\n\nIf you still feel that way after reading this comment then please read [RFC 769](https://github.com/rust-lang/rfcs/blob/master/text/0769-sound-generic-drop.md).\n",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
